# Color palette for plots
colors = [
    "#C4C99C",
    "#669086",
    "#D0685E",
    "#ECBAB0",
    "#C18057",
    "#D7A66C",
    "#D8CFC9",
    "#9EC3B8",
    "#D68F84",
    "#3D5961"
]

binary_color = [
    "#3d85c6",
    "#bcbcbc"
]

def plot_colors(colors):
    n = len(colors)
    cols = n
    rows = 1
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize=(2 * cols, 2 * rows))
    for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flat):
        ax.set_facecolor(colors[i])
        ax.text(0.5, 0.5, colors[i], color='white', fontsize=16, ha='center', va='center')
        ax.set_xticks([])
        ax.set_yticks([])
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

plot_colors(colors)

# Calculate the Sales by day

In [163]:
# Calculate the Sales by day
daily_sales = df.groupby("Order Date", as_index=False)["Sales"].sum().sort_values(by="Order Date")
# Rolling statistics for multiple windows
for window in [7, 30]:
    daily_sales[f"rolling_mean_{window}"] = daily_sales["Sales"].rolling(window, min_periods=1).mean()
    daily_sales[f"rolling_std_{window}"] = daily_sales["Sales"].rolling(window, min_periods=1).std()
    daily_sales[f"rolling_min_{window}"] = daily_sales["Sales"].rolling(window, min_periods=1).min()
    daily_sales[f"rolling_max_{window}"] = daily_sales["Sales"].rolling(window, min_periods=1).max()
    # Lag features: past 1, 7, 30 days sales
for lag in [1, 7, 30]:
    daily_sales[f"sales_lag_{lag}"] = daily_sales["Sales"].shift(lag)


# Visualize the Sales
fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(18,6))

# Daily Sales by each category
category_daily_sales = df.dropna().pivot_table(index="Order Date", columns="Category", values="Sales", aggfunc="sum", fill_value=0)
category_daily_sales = category_daily_sales.reindex(pd.date_range(start=df["Order Date"].min(), end=df["Order Date"].max(), freq="D"), fill_value=0)
category_daily_sales.index.name = "Order Date"

category_list = ["Office Supplies", "Furniture", "Technology"]

for cat in category_list:
  for window in [7, 30]:
    category_daily_sales[f"{cat}_rolling_mean_{window}"] = category_daily_sales[cat].rolling(window, min_periods=1).mean()

# Visualize the daily sales
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize=(18,18))

for i, cat in enumerate(category_list):
  sns.lineplot(category_daily_sales, x=category_daily_sales.index, y=category_list[i], label="Daily Sales", alpha=0.7, ax=axes[i])
  sns.lineplot(category_daily_sales, x=category_daily_sales.index, y=f"{category_list[i]}_rolling_mean_7", label="Rolling Average of 7 days", color="red", ax=axes[i])
  axes[i].set(title=f"Daily Sales of {cat}", xlabel="Date", ylabel="Sales")
  axes[i].legend()

sns.despine()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Bar Plot Function
def categorical_dist(data):
  categorical_bar_list = [var for var in data.columns if data[var].nunique() < 30]

  p = len(categorical_bar_list)
  rows = int(np.ceil(p/3))

  fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, 3, figsize=(12, rows*3))
  axes = axes.flatten()

  for i, var in enumerate(categorical_bar_list):
      sns.countplot(data=data, x=var, color=colors[i % len(colors)], ax=axes[i])
      axes[i].set(title=var, xlabel="", ylabel="Count")
      axes[i].tick_params(axis="x", rotation=90)

  for i in range(len(categorical_bar_list), len(axes)):
    axes[i].axis("off")

  sns.despine()
  plt.tight_layout()

# Box Plot Function
def crosstabplot(data, target):
  categorical_bar_list = [var for var in data.columns if data[var].nunique() < 30]

  p = len(categorical_bar_list)
  rows = int(np.ceil(p/3))

  fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, 3, figsize=(12, rows*4))
  axes = axes.flatten()

  for i, var in enumerate(categorical_bar_list):
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=var, y=target, ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set(title=f"Box Plot of {var}", xlabel=var, ylabel=target.name)
    axes[i].tick_params(axis="x", rotation=90)

  for i in range(len(categorical_bar_list), len(axes)):
    axes[i].axis("off")

  sns.despine()
  plt.tight_layout()

# Check and test the relationship between categorical variables and the target using Welch ANOVA
def categorical_welch(data, categorical, target):
  welch_anova_results = pd.DataFrame()
  for var in categorical:
    welch_test = pg.welch_anova(data=data, dv=target, between=var)
    welch_test["var"] = var
    welch_anova_results = pd.concat([welch_anova_results, welch_test], ignore_index=True)

  return welch_anova_results[["Source", "F", "p-unc"]].sort_values(by='F', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True).style.format({"p-unc": "{:.4f}", "F": "{:.4f}"})

4.5 Dependence Measure¶

In [195]:
def categorical_correlation(data, categorical):
    results = []

    for i in range(len(categorical)):
      for j in range(i+1, len(categorical)):
        var1 = categorical[i]
        var2 = categorical[j]
        contingency_table = pd.crosstab(data[var1], data[var2])

        # Chi-square test
        chi2, p_value, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

        # Cramer's V Calculation
        n = contingency_table.sum().sum()
        phi2 = chi2 / n
        r, k = contingency_table.shape
        cramers_v = np.sqrt(phi2 / (min(r - 1, k - 1)))

        # Append the results
        results.append({
            'Variable 1': var1,
            'Variable 2': var2,
            'Chi-Square': chi2,
            'p-value': p_value,
            "Cramer's V": cramers_v
        })

    pd.options.display.float_format = '{:.4f}'.format
    result = pd.DataFrame(results).sort_values(by="Cramer's V", ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)

    return result

# Transform
def transform(df, features):
  categories = [cat for cat in df["Category"].unique() if pd.notna(cat)]
  output = {}

  # Define full date range
  full_index = pd.date_range(start=df["Order Date"].min(), end=df["Order Date"].max(), freq="D")

  for cat in categories:
    df_cat = df[df["Category"] == cat].copy()
    data = df_cat[features].copy()

    # Agregate by Order Date
    data = data.groupby("Order Date", as_index=False).agg({"Sales": "sum"})

    # Fill the missing dates with Sales = 0
    data = data.set_index("Order Date").reindex(full_index)
    data.index.name= "Order Date"
    data["Sales"] = data["Sales"].fillna(0)
    data = data.reset_index()

    # Log tranform Sales
    data["LSales"] = np.log1p(data["Sales"])

    # Lag Features
    for lag in [1, 7, 15, 21]:
      data[f"Sales.L{lag}"] = data["Sales"].shift(lag)
      data[f"LSales.L{lag}"] = np.log1p(data[f"Sales.L{lag}"])

    # Feature Engineering Order Date
    data["day_of_week"] = data["Order Date"].dt.dayofweek
    data["month"] = data["Order Date"].dt.month
    data["is_weekend"] = data["day_of_week"].isin([5, 6]).astype(int)
    data["quarter"] = data["Order Date"].dt.quarter

    # Cyclical encoding
    for col, max_val in [("day_of_week", 7), ("month", 12), ("quarter", 4)]:
      data[f"{col}_sin"] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * data[col] / max_val)
      data[f"{col}_cos"] = np.cos(2 * np.pi * data[col] / max_val)

    # Set Order Date as index
    data.set_index("Order Date", inplace=True)

    predictors = [col for col in data.columns
                  if (
                      col not in ["Sales", "LSales", "day_of_week", "month", "quarter", "Ship Date"]
                      and not col.startswith("Sales.L"))
                  or col.startswith("Category_") or col.endswith("_log")]

    # Split
    train = data.loc[data.index < cutoff].dropna()
    test = data.loc[data.index >= cutoff].dropna()

    X_train_raw = train[predictors]
    y_train = train["LSales"]
    X_test_raw = test[predictors]
    y_test = test["LSales"]

    # Standard Scaling
    cat_col = [col for col in predictors if col.startswith("Category_") or col in ["is_weekend"]]
    num_col = [col for col in predictors if col not in cat_col]
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_num = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(X_train_raw[num_col]), columns=num_col, index=X_train_raw.index)
    X_test_num = pd.DataFrame(scaler.transform(X_test_raw[num_col]), columns=num_col, index=X_test_raw.index)
    X_train_cat = X_train_raw[cat_col]
    X_test_cat = X_test_raw[cat_col]

    X_train = pd.concat([X_train_num, X_train_cat], axis=1)
    X_test = pd.concat([X_test_num, X_test_cat], axis=1)

    output[cat] = {
        "X_train": X_train,
        "X_test": X_test,
        "y_train": y_train,
        "y_test": y_test,
        "predictors": predictors
    }

  return output

# Time series cross validation (expanding window) function
def tscv_expanding(data, target, model, model_name, n_splits=10):
  tscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=n_splits)
  results = []

  for fold, (train_index, test_index) in enumerate(tscv.split(data)):
    train_df = data.iloc[train_index]
    test_df = data.iloc[test_index]
    y_train = train_df[target]
    y_test = test_df[target]

    # Prediction
    y_pred_log = model(y_train, y_test, train_df, test_df)
    y_test_actual = np.expm1(y_test)
    y_pred_actual = np.expm1(y_pred_log)

    # Evaluate
    mae_score = mae(y_test_actual, y_pred_actual)
    rmse_score = rmse(y_test_actual, y_pred_actual)

    results.append({
        "model": model_name,
        "fold": fold+1,
        "MAE": mae_score,
        "RMSE": rmse_score
    })

  results = pd.DataFrame(results)

  mean_mae = results["MAE"].mean()
  std_mae = results["MAE"].std()
  mean_rmse = results["RMSE"].mean()
  std_rmse = results["RMSE"].std()

  summary_row = pd.DataFrame([{
    "model": results["model"].iloc[0] + " (avg ± std)",
    "fold": "Summary",
    "MAE": f"{mean_mae:.2f} ± {std_mae:.2f}",
    "RMSE": f"{mean_rmse:.2f} ± {std_rmse:.2f}"
  }])

  results = pd.concat([results, summary_row], ignore_index=True)

  return results

# Baseline: Mean
def mean_baseline(y_train, y_test, train_df, test_df):
  mean_y_preds = y_train.mean()

  return np.full(len(y_test), mean_y_preds)

# Baseline: Last Value
def last_baseline(y_train, y_test, train_df, test_df):
  mean_y_preds = y_train.shift(1).iloc[-1]

  return np.full(len(y_test), mean_y_preds)

      X_train_furniture_fold, X_test_furniture_fold = X_train_furniture.iloc[train_index], X_train_furniture.iloc[test_index]

      fold_rmse_scores.append(rmse_score)

    results_list.append({

        "l1_ratio": params["l1_ratio"],
        "mean_MAE": np.mean(fold_mae_scores),
        "std_MAE": np.std(fold_mae_scores),
        "mean_RMSE": np.mean(fold_rmse_scores),
        "std_RMSE": np.std(fold_rmse_scores)

# Office Supplies model
tscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=10)

param_grid = {
    "alpha": [0.01, 0.1, 1.0, 10],
    "l1_ratio": [0.1, 0.5, 0.9]
}
param_list = list(ParameterGrid(param_grid))

results_list = []
for params in param_list:
    fold_mae_scores = []
    fold_rmse_scores = []

    for train_index, test_index in tscv.split(X_train_os):
      X_train_os_fold, X_test_os_fold = X_train_os.iloc[train_index], X_train_os.iloc[test_index]
      y_train_os_fold, y_test_os_fold = y_train_os.iloc[train_index], y_train_os.iloc[test_index]

      model = ElasticNet(**params, max_iter=10000)
      model.fit(X_train_os_fold, y_train_os_fold)
      y_pred_os = model.predict(X_test_os_fold)

      mae_score = mae(np.expm1(y_test_os_fold), np.expm1(y_pred_os))
      rmse_score = rmse(np.expm1(y_test_os_fold), np.expm1(y_pred_os))
      fold_mae_scores.append(mae_score)
      fold_rmse_scores.append(rmse_score)

    results_list.append({
        "alpha": params["alpha"],
        "l1_ratio": params["l1_ratio"],
        "mean_MAE": np.mean(fold_mae_scores),
        "std_MAE": np.std(fold_mae_scores),
        "mean_RMSE": np.mean(fold_rmse_scores),
        "std_RMSE": np.std(fold_rmse_scores)
    })

result_table = pd.DataFrame(results_list).sort_values(by="mean_MAE").reset_index(drop=True)
result_table
